Comment: We've never seen Tyrion angry before, not really.Peter Dinklage's epic courtroom confession, one of the best in recent television, dances along the edge of overwrought during the "on trial for being a dwarf" moment.

EpisodeTitle: 6. The Laws of Gods and Men
Comment: [Dinklage] absolutely sells out for the scene, and his monologue is spectacular. After a few slow moving episodes, this moment feels like the highwater point of the show's midpoint.

EpisodeTitle: 6. The Laws of Gods and Men
Comment: There's just something about watching characters go to the bank to apply for a loan that isn't as exciting to me as, say, oh I don't know, people getting swords put through their faces.

EpisodeTitle: 6. The Laws of Gods and Men
Comment: The trial of Tyrion comes late in "The Laws of Gods and Men," a move that allows the episode an opportunity to end on a high note.

EpisodeTitle: 6. The Laws of Gods and Men
Comment: An episode that was quickly turning into redundant filler, was saved by a refreshing kangaroo court.

EpisodeTitle: 6. The Laws of Gods and Men
Comment: Realizing he'll find no justice in this court of men, Tyrion Lannister (Peter Dinklage) wants the gods to decide his fate. "I demand a trial by combat," he declares.

EpisodeTitle: 6. The Laws of Gods and Men
Comment: Tyrion's fierce, contemptuous courtroom speech was the highlight of this week's visit to Westeros. You could feel his pain during Shae's testimony and almost see the moment he decided he was just DONE with the whole King's Landing lot.

EpisodeTitle: 6. The Laws of Gods and Men
Comment: The Laws of Gods and Men is a visually stunning entry into this season's run, but its strengths rely on Tyrion's futile battle with justice.

But in the words of Arya Stark, "not today" - at least not for most of them - and it's that choice that makes "The Long Night" feel like a great thrill, massive relief and slight disappointment at the same time.

In terms of sheer spectacle, no other episode of Game of Thrones rivals the scale or ambition of "The Long Night," with Miguel Sapochnik expertly balancing the many character plot threads while building a tangible sense of dread.
